data:
So picking up where we left off, the campaign really started to gain traction after the second week.
Yeah, I saw the numbers this morning.
The click through rate jumped, right?
Exactly, up by almost eighteen percent.
And what's interesting is that the engagement stayed consistent even after the initial push.
That's rare.
Usually we see a drop off after the first few days.
Do we know why it held steady?
My guess is the creative refresh we rolled out midweek.
It gave people something new to engage with without changing the core message.
Makes sense.
What about audience segments?
Any surprises there?
Actually, yes, the younger group responded better than the older group, which is the opposite of what we expected.
Interesting.
Maybe the visuals appealed more to a younger demographic.
Possibly.
I think the tone of the copy played a part too.
It was a bit more playful than our usual style.
Do you think we should lean into that for the next campaign?
I think we should test it.
Maybe we can run a split test, one with a playful tone, one more traditional.
I like that, and we should also keep an eye on cost per acquisition.
If we can get it down by even ten percent, that's a big win.
Agreed.
Oh, and one more thing, the retargeting ads performed way better than expected.
Really?
Yeah, conversion rates were up compared to last month.
We might want to increase the retargeting budget next quarter.
Got it.
I'll make a note of that.
Anything else before we wrap?
Just that we need to finalize the content calendar by Friday, that way we can hit the ground running for the next cycle.
Perfect.
I'll draft it up and send it over later today.
Sounds good, thanks.
